Defendant Tracy Wayne Smith in court with attorney Louis E Epps.  Defendant Tracy Wayne Smith in custody.  Jay R Pucek appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties advise the Court that they have reached a resolution in this matter.    Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, and further advised that if not a United States citizen deportation is possible. Defendant sworn, examined as to plea, and entered a plea of NO CONTEST.  Court found defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived all constitutional rights. Plea questionnaire waiver of rights and addendum to plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulated to the criminal complaint as factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered into the record.  The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms. Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  

The Court imposed but stayed 9 months at the House of Correction, with Huber and good time allowed, credit for 116 days time served, and placed defendant on probation for one (1) year.

The Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample, unless previously provided.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
 - No controlled substances or alcohol;
 - AODA assessment; treatment if needed;
 - Urine screens;
 - Obtain GED;
 - Seek and maintain employment;
 - Job and vocational training;
 - Cognitive thinking intervention counseling;
 - Parenting classes/counseling;
 - Pay the DNA surcharge, costs and disbursements Failure to pay by the end of probationary term would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant which is non-dischargable in bankruptcy.

As no restitution was requested, Court set restitution at zero.

Should defendant successfully complete all conditions set forth by this Court, the Probation Department/Department of Corrections, pay all costs and surcharges and remain free and clear of the criminal justice system arising to the level of probable cause, the Court would consider petition for expungement.

Filed,
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief;
